Gemini said
Yes, you can absolutely use Gemini from your command line using the OpenAI library, but there are some critical distinctions regarding billing and how it compares to Google's own dedicated CLI.

1. Using Gemini via the OpenAI Library
Google provides an OpenAI-compatible endpoint, meaning you can use the openai Python package or CLI to talk to Gemini by simply changing the base_url.

To do this in Python:

Python
from openai import OpenAI

client = OpenAI(
    api_key="YOUR_GEMINI_API_KEY",
    base_url="https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/openai/"
)

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="gemini-1.5-flash", # or gemini-1.5-pro
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Hello from the CLI!"}]
)
print(response.choices[0].message.content)
2. The "Billing" and Token Question
This is the most important part: Using the API is NOT the same as using the web interface.

gemini.google.com (Web): Usually offers a "free-to-use" experience (with a monthly subscription for the "Advanced" model) that doesn't track tokens in a billing sense.

Gemini API (via OpenAI library or Google SDK): This is governed by Google AI Studio tiers.

Free Tier: You can use Gemini 1.5 Flash and Pro for free up to certain rate limits (e.g., 15 requests per minute for Pro). However, in the free tier, Google reserves the right to use your data to improve their models.

Paid Tier: If you enable billing to get higher limits or data privacy, you are billed per 1,000 tokens, exactly like OpenAI.

Warning: If you want to avoid "counting and billing tokens," you must ensure your Google AI Studio project remains on the Free Tier. If you attach a credit card and "Pay-as-you-go," you will be charged per token.

3. Google Gemini CLI vs. OpenAI TUI
Google recently released an official Gemini CLI (often run via npx @google/gemini-cli), which is a dedicated "AI Agent" for your terminal. Here is how it stacks up against using a generic OpenAI-based TUI:

Feature	Official Gemini CLI (gemini-cli)	OpenAI-compatible TUI (e.g., aichat)
Context	Massive 1-million+ token context window support.	Often limited by the TUI's buffer or standard OpenAI headers.
System Access	Can read/write files and run shell commands (Agentic).	Mostly restricted to text-in, text-out.
Features	Includes Google Search grounding and MCP support.	Limited to what the model knows or basic RAG.
Ease of Use	Just run npx @google/gemini-cli—no API key needed if you sign in via browser.	Requires manual API key and base_url configuration.
Cost Control	Defaults to the free tier (1,000 requests/day).	Depends entirely on your API key settings.
Advantages of the Gemini CLI:
Codebase Awareness: You can point it at a local folder, and it can analyze your entire project because of the huge context window.

Multimodal: It can handle images/files directly from your terminal.

Built-in Tools: It can actually execute the code it writes to test if it works (with your permission).

Disadvantages:
Privacy: The free tier of the CLI uses the same "data for training" policy as the Free API.

Heaviness: It’s more of an "agent" than a simple chat interface, which might be overkill if you just want a quick answer.

Summary Recommendation
If you want the "same service" as the web but in the terminal:

Get a Free API Key from Google AI Studio.

Try the official CLI first: Run npx @google/gemini-cli. It is the most powerful way to use Gemini in a dev environment without worrying about per-token billing (as long as you stay in the free daily quota).

Use the OpenAI library only if you are building your own custom script or already have a TUI you love that allows changing the base_url.





